FUNGAL INFECTION, CONTAMINATED DRUG - USA (09):NEW OUTBREAK, REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
************************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Fri 31 May 2013
Source: WSIL TV, Associated Press (AP) report [edited]
http://www.wsiltv.com/news/local/IDPH-2-New-Infections-Tied-to-Steroid-Injections-209715291.html


Illinois health officials say they're investigating 2 additional reports of patients developing abscesses after receiving potentially contaminated steroid injections at a clinic. The Illinois Department of Public Health said on Fri 31 May 2013 that the additional patients -- like the earlier cases -- had received injections at the Logan Primary Care clinic in the Williamson County town of Herrin. Last week [week of 20 May 2013], the state health department announced that 5 patients had developed similar infections after the injections.

The steroid is methylprednisolone acetate, and was produced by a compounding pharmacy in Tennessee. The pharmacy has voluntarily recalled all its sterile products. The steroid is the same drug [as was] at the center of last year's [2012] deadly outbreak of fungal meningitis, caused by contaminated injections from a Massachusetts compounding pharmacy.

Health officials say no cases of meningitis have been reported.

